Pickled red onions 🤤🧅
Here’s the thing- I’m an onion girl through and through. I think onions (and garlic!) make everything better!!

This was my first time making pickled red onions and it was super easy. Great on bagels, tacos, burgers, salads, toast- you name it!! 

Recipe—
• In a mason or air tight jar, add thinly sliced red onions (one medium or two small)
• In a small saucepan, heat 1/2 cup of white or apple cider vinegar, 2tsp salt, and a drizzle of honey (or spoonful of sugar if you prefer).
• Mix on low heat until dissolved and pour over onions once room temperature 
• Add 1/2 cup of warm water to onion vinegar mixrure
• Add in any additional seasonings you prefer- here I just did garlic powder and salt, but you could also do garlic cloves, peppercorn, etc!
• Seal onion mixture tightly and store in the fridge - I like to do so overnight. They’ll be ready when they’re tender and bright pink and keep well in the fridge for several weeks! 

Tag me if you try them- they add the perfect flair to any meal!

LEMON CHICKEN SOUP 🍜 

Bringing back one of my favorite soup recipes- perfect for a cold winter day & very simple to make. Recipe below—

•Cook down 3 stalls chopped celery, 5 diced carrots, and a diced onion in a Dutch oven or large pot
•Push veggies too the side and sear 2 chicken breasts in the pot on both sides.
•Cover with broth (I used vegetable but any works)
•Add other veggies of choice- here i did mushrooms, peas, and spinach 
•Squeeze the juice of two lemons into the pot 
•Let simmer for 45 minutes before shredding the chicken and adding it back into the soup
•Temper 2 egg yolks + 1 egg with a bit of the broth before mixing it into the soup (makes it creamy!)
•Add some fresh parsley over too and enjoy!!

VEGGIE EGG BITES 🍳🫑🧅

Inspired by the Starbucks sous vide egg bites- they get a lot of hype and let me tell you- they live up to it 🤩

The trick is blending cottage cheese into the egg mixture for an extra creamy texture (+ extra protein!) Recipe below! Makes 12 egg bites.

• To a food processor or blender, add 4 whole eggs, 1 cup of egg whites, and 1 cup of cottage cheese
• Season with salt, pepper, garlic powder, onion salt
• First pulse, then blend the mixture until super smoothe and set aside
• Cook your fillings- this time I sautéed green and red onions, mushrooms, and tomatoes until soft- but you can use any veggie or meat of your choosing. Breakfast meat would be great!
• Spray a cupcake tin with oil to prevent sticking
• Add an equal amount of filling to each cup and pour the egg mixture over top, filling 3/4 of the way 
• Add cheese to the top and mix in if desired (I used sharp cheddar)
• Bake at 350 for 18-22 minutes, until the eggs are brown around the edges and fully cooked!
• ENJOY!!!

I’ve been taking these to work all week- they’re so simple to make, easy to reheat in both the microwave and toaster oven, and a great chance of pace from my usual hard boiled eggs / oatmeal. ☺️

EASY TUNA SALAD 🐟🥗 

I’ve been a tuna salad girl since I was a kid. It was one of the few foods my dad & I bonded over. Lately, I’ve been focusing on eating more protein & tuna salad is a great source of it!!

• In a bowl, break up one can of tuna (I’m using albacore solid white tuna in water) with a fork until the pieces are small/fine
• Add two stalks chopped celery, red + green onion, and a few chopped dill + bread and butter pickles (secret ingredient!!)
• Add a tablespoon of light mayo,teaspoon of spicy mustard, and a few drops of sriracha. These are rough measurements- I eyeball
• Season with pepper, garlic powder, paprika- whatever you have and whatever you like!
• Mix, refrigerate, and serve! I like it on toasted GF bread or over some spring mix and baby tomatoes with balsamic 😊

Sweet potato protein pancakes 🥞🍠
The perfect balance of sweet, cinnamon, & vanilla from the protein- my ideal post workout breakfast.

RECIPE: save for later!! 😊
• 1 medium sized cooked sweet potato (I baked in foil for 40 minutes on 350)
• 1/4 cup flour of choice (I used GF all purpose)
• 1/2 tablespoon brown sugar 
• 1 tablespoon egg whites 
• 1 scoop vanilla protein powder 
• 1 teaspoon baking powder 
• cinnamon + pumpkin pie spice (optional)
• 1/3 cup Almond milk

Mash the cooked sweet potato in a bowl and add all other ingredients minus the milk. Combine and slowly add the milk while mixing until you get a pancake batter consistency. Once the batter is smooth, add the batter to a pan on medium high heat. Flip when bubbling. Serve with low sugar syrup and enjoy!! 

Makes 2 large pancakes- good for one person 🥰

At 19, I was battling my mental health and I was at war with my body. I was a college student who wasn’t even self aware enough to really understand how deep in the trenches I was.

Fast forward five years and I have what I always wanted: I have a healthy relationship with food + my body, a happy relationship, the sweetest rescue pup, an amazing community at F45, hobbies and passions, a sense of self, and some of the most amazing friends I could ask for.

I saw this Lightening McQueen trend and it made me think about how proud the past versions of myself are of me now.

Life can be hard and the hard times feel long- and then suddenly, the 19 year old version of yourself is cheering the 27 year old version of yourself on. 🤍

Somewhere between then and now, healing happened 🤍

I tried every diet in the book. Every “healthy food swap”. Every elimination diet. Every variation of fasting. I spent hours a week on the treadmill, I started a lot of days with black coffee on an empty stomach, I told myself 1400 calories as a highly active person was maintainable. I criticized myself every time I looked in the mirror.

I was at war with my body and my mind for years, and I’ll spend the rest of my life making it up to myself. Pushing my body to be strong and my mind to be stronger. Never depriving myself again of the things I love, whether it be a bagel or half baked ice cream or anything inbetween. Never again missing out on LIFE in fear of the way my body may look in a photo.

Healing happens. It takes a lot of work and lot of hard conversations with yourself- but let me be the proof that healing your relationship with your body and with food is possible, and so so worth it. 🤍

Simplest shrimp tacos 🍤🌮🤤
A very easy meal for any night of the week!!

PREP:
1. I buy the thin corn tortillas because they’re gluten free and toast up nicely. I throw them right on the open flame on my stovetop to get that char!
3. The slaw is so easy- buy a bag of cole slaw or broccoli slaw mix, season a cup of it with paprika, garlic powder, and chipotle seasoning, add a tablespoon of mayo and the juice of a lime, some diced red onion, and put in the fridge an hour before serving. The lime breaks down the slaw mix and all the flavors meld together!
2. I keep an eye on the frozen shrimp at stop and shop- it goes on sale a lot!! For these, I thawed 9 jumbo shrimp in the fridge, seasoned with garlic powder, paprika, and chipotle seasoning, and seared for 2 minutes per side on high.

ASSEMBLY:
•char/heat your corn tortillas to your liking 
•spoon in some of your slaw mix
•add seared shrimp or fish of your liking 
•slice an avocado and add to each taco
•top with a good squeeze of lime juice and fresh cilantro
•add any extra slaw on top!! The more the better

THE DEETS👇
In a medium sized bowl, add
* 3/4 cup almond flour
* 1/2 teaspoon baking soda
* 1 teaspoon baking powder
* 1/2 cup protein powder
* 1/4 teaspoon salt

In a large bowl, mash 2 ripened bananas until the consistency is smooth. Then add:
* 1 egg
* Splash of vanilla or almond extract
* 2 tablespoon honey or maple syrup
* Sprinkle of sugar or stevia

The egg bites are BACK 🍳
I’ve shared the recipe before but since I make + post these delicious little egg bites for breakfast every week, I’m always trying different variations!!

These are a mozzerella, zucchini & mushroom egg white blend and they came out great. Recipe below ⤵️

• Start by dicing and cooking any vegetables you’re adding to your egg cups- here I’m using onion, zucchini + mushroom. Cook until semi soft but not cooked all the way
• To a food processor or blender, add 2 whole eggs, 1 small carton (10 servings) of egg whites, and 1 small cup of cottage cheese
• Season with salt, pepper, garlic powder, onion salt
• First pulse, then blend the mixture until super smooth
• Spray a muffin tin with oil to prevent sticking
• Add an equal amount of vegetable filling to each cup and pour the egg mixture over top
• Add a sprinkle of LF mozzerella cheese to the top and mix it in
• Bake at 350 for 18-22 minutes, until the eggs are brown around the edges and fully cooked!
• ENJOY!!! 

I pack these for work breakfast every day- they’re so simple to make, easy to reheat in both the microwave and toaster oven, and a great hot breakfast option that’s high in protein 🤌🏼

5 INGREDIENT TURKEY BURGERS 🍔
I know what you’re thinking- nobody likes turkey burgers- they’re dry and they get a bad rep. Not these!!!

These five ingredient burgers are kept moist by creamy feta + fresh spinach. Serve with a side of fresh sweet potato fries and it’s the perfect high protein lunch or weeknight dinner 🥬🍠🥒

THE BURGS:
• in a large mixing bowl, add half a diced onion, one cup chopped spinach, 1lb (16oz) of ground turkey or chicken, and 4oz (half a block) of feta, crumbled
• season with salt, pepper, garlic powder, and onion salt
• mix before cracking an egg and really combining (use your hands for best mixing😊)
• mold into five burgers and cook for a few minutes per side in a pan on medium high heat (I cut into the thickest part of the burger to ensure they’re fully cooked through
• Serve with your favorite burger accoutrements!! I did a bed of spinach, sliced tomato, red onion, extra pickles and a drizzle of tzatziki 
• for my sweet potato fries, I just cut the sweet potato into equal sized fry shapes and air fryed at 400 degrees for 10 minutes, shaking once!

I spent the whole month of November under the weather which resulted in spending an absurd amount of money on “Mama’s chicken soup” from Whole Foods. SO good but also- SO easy to make at home!!

I think the trick to a perfect soup is to SEASON generously. Fresh herbs, dried spices, and seasoning is what transforms chicken broth to a warm and hearty soup.

The recipe-
•in a crockpot, season 1.5lb chicken breast with salt, pepper, garlic powder, onion powder and cook on high for 4 hours. I do this because I like a tender chicken in my soup (also threw some fresh thyme and rosemary in for flavor)
•in a dutch oven or large pot, sautee one small diced onion, a tablespoon of minced garlic, 5 stalks of chopped celery and 7 large chopped carrots 
•pour in a little bit of chicken broth and let simmer until carrots are soft
•once soft, add an entire carton of chicken broth, a tablespoon of chopped fresh parsley, a tablespoon of thyme, and a sprig of rosemary. Taste your broth and season accordingly!
•bring to a simmer for 30 minutes to let the flavors merry. At this point, I also add the cooked chicken in to absorb the flavor 
•after about 30 minutes, shred the chicken and add back to the pot. Season again and serve!

For this bowl, I added some gluten free pastina along with fresh grated parm. You can cook the pastina in the simmering soup if desired- just be sure to add extra broth because the pasta will absorb a lot. 🍜
